TY  - JOUR
T1  - Leveraging Knowledge Across Geographic Boundaries
AU  - Tallman, Stephen
AU  - Phene, Anupama
Y1  - 2007/04/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1060.0227
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1060.0227
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 252
EP  - 260
VL  - 18
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines knowledge flows within and across geographic boundaries of clusters and nations in the biotechnology industry. We hypothesize that these flows are characterized by various factors relating to the knowledge itself and by firm innovativeness and the presence of prior knowledge flows at the firm level. Surprisingly, our findings suggest that geographic proximity does not matter in some instances, while in others it has a decidedly nonlinear effect opposite to that hypothesized. The pattern of findings points to the greatest contrast in the comparison of between-cluster and between-country flows and presents an opportunity to reevaluate the role of geography and knowledge flows.
AB  - This paper examines knowledge flows within and across geographic boundaries of clusters and nations in the biotechnology industry. We hypothesize that these flows are characterized by various factors relating to the knowledge itself and by firm innovativeness and the presence of prior knowledge flows at the firm level. Surprisingly, our findings suggest that geographic proximity does not matter in some instances, while in others it has a decidedly nonlinear effect opposite to that hypothesized. The pattern of findings points to the greatest contrast in the comparison of between-cluster and between-country flows and presents an opportunity to reevaluate the role of geography and knowledge flows.
